     Fix 403 Forbidden Error on Customer Order Stats Update

     Problem Analysis

     The Customer Service is returning 403 Forbidden when Order Service tries to update customer statistics after order creation. Despite adding @PreAuthorize annotation, 
     the issue persists.

     Root Cause: The Order Service's CustomerServiceClient is NOT forwarding the JWT Authorization header when making the REST call to Customer Service. The 
     @PreAuthorize("hasAnyRole('MANAGER', ...)") annotation requires Spring Security authentication context which is only populated by the JWT token's "roles" claim - HTTP
      headers like X-User-Type: MANAGER are NOT sufficient.

     Investigation Findings

     1. @PreAuthorize annotation is correctly applied at CustomerController.java:382
     2. JwtForwardingInterceptor exists but may not be functioning properly in all contexts
     3. CustomerServiceClient creates HttpEntity without Authorization header
     4. JwtAuthenticationFilter requires valid JWT to populate security context
     5. X-User-Type header alone is insufficient - Spring Security needs actual role authorities from JWT

     Solution Plan

     Approach: Ensure JWT Token Forwarding in CustomerServiceClient

     Modify the CustomerServiceClient to explicitly extract and forward the JWT Authorization header from the current request context to the Customer Service.

     Critical Files

     1. /order-service/src/main/java/com/MaSoVa/order/client/CustomerServiceClient.java - Add JWT forwarding
     2. /order-service/src/main/java/com/MaSoVa/order/config/JwtForwardingInterceptor.java - Verify functionality
     3. /customer-service/src/main/java/com/MaSoVa/customer/controller/CustomerController.java - Already has @PreAuthorize (no changes)

     Implementation Steps

     Step 1: Verify JwtForwardingInterceptor Configuration

     - Check that JwtForwardingInterceptor is properly registered with RestTemplate in RestTemplateConfig
     - Ensure it's being invoked for CustomerServiceClient calls
     - Add debug logging to confirm header forwarding

     Step 2: Modify CustomerServiceClient for Explicit JWT Forwarding

     Add method to extract JWT from current request context:

     private String getJwtFromCurrentRequest() {
         try {
             ServletRequestAttributes attributes =
                 (ServletRequestAttributes) RequestContextHolder.getRequestAttributes();
             if (attributes != null) {
                 HttpServletRequest request = attributes.getRequest();
                 String bearerToken = request.getHeader("Authorization");
                 if (StringUtils.hasText(bearerToken) && bearerToken.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
                     return bearerToken.substring(7);
                 }
             }
         } catch (Exception e) {
             log.warn("Could not extract JWT from request context", e);
         }
         return null;
     }

     Update updateOrderStats method to include Authorization header:

     public void updateOrderStats(String customerId, String status, double orderTotal) {
         if (customerId == null || customerId.trim().isEmpty()) {
             log.debug("Skipping order stats update - no customer ID provided");
             return;
         }

         try {
             String url = customerServiceUrl + "/api/customers/" + customerId + "/order-stats";

             Map<String, Object> request = new HashMap<>();
             request.put("status", status);
             request.put("orderTotal", orderTotal);

             HttpHeaders headers = new HttpHeaders();
             headers.setContentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON);

             // Add JWT Authorization header
             String jwt = getJwtFromCurrentRequest();
             if (jwt != null) {
                 headers.set("Authorization", "Bearer " + jwt);
                 log.debug("Added Authorization header for customer stats update");
             } else {
                 log.warn("No JWT token available - customer stats update may fail with 403");
             }

             HttpEntity<Map<String, Object>> entity = new HttpEntity<>(request, headers);

             ResponseEntity<String> response = restTemplate.postForEntity(url, entity, String.class);

             if (response.getStatusCode().is2xxSuccessful()) {
                 log.info("Successfully updated order stats for customer: {}", customerId);
             }
         } catch (Exception e) {
             log.error("Error updating customer order stats for customer: {}. Order Total: {}",
                      customerId, orderTotal, e);
         }
     }

